# Day 7 - Secure Root SSH Access

## Task
Disable direct root SSH login on all App servers in the Stratos Datacenter.

## Objective
Harden SSH access by preventing direct root login and verifying the service reload on each server.

## Commands Used
```bash
ssh tony@stapp01
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
sudo grep PermitRootLogin /etc/ssh/sshd_config
sudo systemctl restart sshd
sudo systemctl status sshd
```

Repeat the same process on `stapp02` and `stapp03`.

## What the Commands Do
- `ssh tony@stapp01` connects to App Server 1.
- `sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config` edits the SSH daemon configuration.
- `sudo grep PermitRootLogin /etc/ssh/sshd_config` verifies the active setting.
- `sudo systemctl restart sshd` reloads SSH with the new configuration.
- `sudo systemctl status sshd` confirms the daemon is running.

## Verification
Confirmed `PermitRootLogin no` on each server and verified that `sshd` was active after restart.

## What I Learned
- How to harden SSH by disabling direct root login.
- Why config changes require restarting `sshd`.
- The difference between `ssh` and `sshd` service names on RHEL-based systems.
- Why each server should be checked individually instead of assuming identical config.

## Personal Notes
This task reinforced the importance of verifying the configuration on every server, because not all systems started with the same SSH settings. It also showed that checking service status after a restart is a good habit for change validation.
